{"parse":{"title":"country","pageid":2068,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"==English==\n{{wp|<dab>}}\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alter|en|contree|countrey||archaic}}\n* {{alter|en|contrey|countre|countrie|counterie||obsolete}}\n* {{alter|en|counthry||pronunciation spelling}}\n* {{alter|en|cuntry||eye dialect|derogatory}}\n\n===Etymology===\n{{ety|en|:inh|enm:contre<ref:{{R:Etymonline|pos=n}}<<name::0>>>|tree=1|text=++}} Cognate with {{cog|sco|kintra}}. Unrelated to {{m|en|county}}. Displaced native {{m+|en|land}} in some of its senses.\n\nFrom around 1300 as \"area surrounding a walled city or town; the open country.\" By early 16th century the sense was applied mostly to rural areas, as opposed to towns and cities.<ref name=\":0\"/>\n\nCompare typologically {{m+|ru|страна́}}, {{m|ru|сторона́}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{enPR|kŭn'tri}}\n** {{IPA|en|/ˈkʌntɹi/|[ˈkʰʌnt̠ɹ̠̊˔ʷi]|a=UK,US,CA}}\n*** {{audio|en|en-uk-country.ogg|a=UK}}\n*** {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Naomi Persephone Amethyst (NaomiAmethyst)-country.wav|a=GA}}\n*** {{audio|en|en-us-country.ogg|a=US}}\n** {{IPA|en|/ˈkɐntɹi/|a=AuE,NZ}}\n** {{IPA|en|/ˈkən.ʈri/|[kɐn.t̺riˑ]|a=Indic}}\n** {{rhymes|en|ʌntɹi|s=2}}\n* {{enPR|koun'tri|a=common for [[ESL]] speakers|q=proscribed}}, {{IPA|en|/ˈkaʊntɹi/}}\n** {{rhymes|en|aʊntɹi|s=2}}\n* {{hyphenation|en|coun|try}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{en-noun|~}}\n\n# {{senseid|en|territory of a nation; nation state; sovereign state}} The territory of a [[nation]]; a [[sovereign state]] or a [[region]] once independent and still distinct in [[institutions]], [[language]], etc. {{defdate|from 14th c.}}\n#: {{syn|en|Thesaurus:country}}\n#: {{hypo|en|LMIC<id:low- or middle-income country>|HIC<id:high-income country>|developing country|developed country|member country|mini-country|old country|Thesaurus:country}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1935|author=[https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/288354.George_Goodchild George Goodchild]\n|title=Death on the Centre Court|chapter=5\n|passage=By one o'clock the place was choc-a-bloc. {{...}} The restaurant was packed, and the promenade between the two main courts and the subsidiary courts was thronged with healthy-looking youngish people, drawn to the Mecca of tennis from all parts of the '''country'''.}}\n#* {{quote-av|en|author= w:Michael Parenti|date= 15 April 1986|location= {{w|Boulder, Colorado|Boulder}}, {{w|Colorado}}\n|title= U.S. interventionism, the Third World, and the USSR\n|url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xP8CzlFhc14&t=173s|time= 02:53\n|text= But that expropriation of the Third World, [that] has been going on for 400 years, brings us to another revelation: namely, that the Third World is not poor. You don't go to poor '''countries''' to make money. There are very few poor '''countries''' in this world. Most '''countries''' are rich: the Philippines are rich, Brazil is rich, Mexico is rich, Chile is rich; only the people are poor. But there's billions to be made there, to be carved out, and to be taken; there's been billions for 400 years! The Capitalist European and North American powers have carved out and taken the timber, the flax, the hemp, the cocoa, the rum, the tin, the copper, the iron, the rubber, the bauxite, the slaves, and the cheap labour. They have taken out of these '''countries'''. These '''countries''' are not underdeveloped; they're overexploited!}}\n#* {{RQ:Mandela Long Walk to Freedom|year=2010|page=3|passage=It is a beautiful '''country''' of rolling hills, fertile valleys, and a thousand rivers and streams which keep the landscape green even in winter.}}\n#* '''2010''', ''The Economist'', 3 Feb 2011:\n#*: These days corporate Germany looks rather different. Volkswagen, the '''country'''’s leading carmaker, wants to be the world’s biggest by 2018.\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=2013-06-22|volume=407|issue=8841|page=68|magazine=w:The Economist\n|url=http://www.economist.com/news/finance-and-economics/21579860-g8-pledges-tackle-three-ts-t-time|title=T time\n|passage=The ability to shift profits to low-tax '''countries''' by locating intellectual property in them, which is then licensed to related businesses in high-tax '''countries''', is often assumed to be the preserve of high-tech companies.|archiveurl=https://archive.ph/JN1ea|archivedate=2023-03-11}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|author=Lilit Marcus|title=This country has a national happiness index. But what is it really like to live there?|magazine=w:CNN|url=https://www.cnn.com/travel/life-in-bhutan-intl-hnk/index.html|date=2024-07-04|passage=Most foreigners who have heard of Bhutan know two things: the '''country''' charges international visitors a $100/day sustainable development fee (aka tourist tax), and that it is the birthplace of the Gross National Happiness Index, a system intended to look after the well-being of citizens and the environment.|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20240724100055/https://www.cnn.com/travel/life-in-bhutan-intl-hnk/index.html}}\n# {{senseid|en|area, district, region}} {{lb|en|especially|_|Britain|uncountable|countable}} An [[area]] of land of undefined extent; a [[region]], a [[district]]. {{defdate|from 13th c.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|author=David Vann|journal=w:The Observer|date=2010-03-07\n|passage=We walk along flat, open '''country''', red dirt and spinifex grass, a few short trees{{nb...}}.}}\n## {{senseid|en|region of land delimited by certain factors}} {{lb|en|uncountable|countable}} An [[area]] of land of indefinite extent or of more or less definite extent in relation to human occupation, especially characterized by its particular [[physical]] [[features]], or its suitability for a particular [[activity]] or connected with its [[population]] (by [[race]], [[dialect]], [[culture]], etc.) or a [[person]], especially a writer, or their [[works]].\n##: {{hypo|en|backcountry|high country|north country|upcountry}}\n##: {{uxi|en|Thomas Hardy '''country'''}}\n##: {{ux|en|Hikers love the wild '''country''' that lies northwest of this river confluence.}}\n##* {{quote-journal|en|author=Chris Moss|journal=w:The Guardian|date=2007-02-17\n|passage=This is condor '''country''' – the only region this far east where you can see the magnificent vulture – and a small national park straddling the passes, El Condorito, is a good stopover for walkers and birders.}}\n# {{senseid|en|the country, rural area, as opposed to the town or city}} {{lb|en|uncountable|usually preceded by “the”}} A rural area, as opposed to a [[town]] or [[city]]; the [[countryside]]. {{defdate|from 16th c.}}\n<!--In attributive position, such as with {{collocation|en|'''country''' mouse and city mouse}} or {{collocation|en|'''country''' shopkeeper}}, might one say that the status as noun adjunct versus true adjective depends on the utterance and the era? If you [[go country]], then things are just a little more '''country''' than you've been used to.-->\n#* {{RQ:Montaigne Florio Essayes|chapter=17|book=II|passage=I was borne and brought up in the '''Countrie''', and amidst husbandry{{nb...}}.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=4 Mar 2000|author=Alexander Chancellor|journal=The Guardian\n|passage=I have always thought that one of the main reasons for the popularity of blood sports in the '''country''' is the pointlessness of going outdoors with no purpose or destination in mind.}}\n#* {{quote-book\n|en\n|url=https://archive.org/details/englishpenguindictionaryofliterary/Difficulties_in_Learning_English_as_a_Se/\n|year=2006\n|month=May\n|author=James B. Weld\n|title=Difficulties in Learning English as a Second or Foreign Language\n|publisher=w:Regis University\n|page=37\n|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/englishpenguindictionaryofliterary/Difficulties_in_Learning_English_as_a_Se/page/n40/\n|passage=She grew up in Chang-hua, a city in central Taiwan with a decidedly '''country''' flavor.}}\n# The [[inhabitants]] or [[people]] of a [[district]], [[region]], or [[nation]]; the [[populace]], the [[public]]. {{defdate|from ca. 1300}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|title=w:Henry IV, Part 2|year=c. 1596–1599|author=w:William Shakespeare|text=For all the '''country''', in a general voice,<br/>Cried hate upon him.|volume_plain=Act 4, Scene 1|line=2344|lineurl=https://www.opensourceshakespeare.org/views/plays/play_view.php?WorkID=henry4p2&Act=4&Scene=1&Scope=scene&LineHighlight=2336#2336|source=Open Source Shakespeare}}\n# {{senseid|en|traditional lands of Indigenous people}} {{lb|en|Australia|usually capitalised}} [[traditional|Traditional]] lands of [[Indigenous]] people with [[embed]]ded [[cultural]], [[spiritual]], [[cosmological]], [[ecological]], and [[physical]] attributes and values.\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=16 Feb 1842|journal=The Inquirer|location=Perth|page=5|column=2|text=\"Me like my '''country''' — no much too hot, no much too cold. By and bye, white fellow come — soldier-man come. White fellow say, ''this'' our land, ''that'' our land — ALL '''country''' our land. Black fellow say no! my '''country''' no white fellow's '''country''', and black fellow take spear.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=27 Sep 1945|journal=The Chronicle|location=Adelaide|page=35|column=4|text=\"Yewi,\" he said, \"me bin longa Fanny Bay gaol five years.\" On my asking why they put him in gaol he replied. \"Australia your '''country''', ain't it?\" I replied, \"Yes, him my '''country''' all right.\" \"Well,\" he then said, \"this my '''country''' here. Brinken '''country''' other side of the river ain't it?\" \"That's right,\" said I. \"Well,\" said Jack, \"supposem Japanese come longa this '''country''' and you killem, you good man, but suppose Brinken come longa my '''country''' here, and I kill him, police man put me longa Fanny Bay for five years. That is the law.\" }}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=23 July 2008|journal=The Torres News|page=5|column=1|text=\"It demonstrates that having Indigenous people on '''country''' managing their lands, delivering environmental benefits for all Australians is an important asset for the national good.\"}}\n#* {{RQ:Guardian|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20221007031547/https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2015/mar/11/of-three-remote-communities-here-why-are-only-the-two-aboriginal-ones-under-threat|author=Calla Wahlquist|title=Of three remote communities here, why are only the two Aboriginal ones under threat?|date=11 March 2015|passage=Milgin says living on '''country''', with elders, makes Aboriginal people \"strong\". That's backed up by a 2011 report on Aboriginal homelands by Amnesty International that found that living on homelands was connected to better health outcomes and drug rehabilitation.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=8 July 2021|journal=The Air Force News|page=16|column=2|text=What '''country''' do you live/work on? I work on Yuggera Yuggarapul '''country''' and I'm from Darwin, Larrakia '''country'''. }}\n# {{senseid|en|country music, elliptically}} {{ellipsis of|en|country music}}. {{defdate|from 20th c.}}\n#: {{ux|en|a '''country''' song}}\n#: {{ux|en|a '''country''' singer}}\n#: {{ux|en|a '''country''' festival}}\n# {{senseid|en|spirit of country folkways}} {{lb|en|informal}} The [[spirit#Noun|spirit]] of the [[#English:_the country, rural area, as opposed to the town or city|country]] (rural places): the spirit of country [[folkway]]s; those folkways.\n#: {{collocation|en|you can take the boy out of the country, but you can't take the '''country''' out of the boy}}\n<!--[[Appendix:Snowclones/you can take X out of Y, but you can't take Y out of X]]-->\n<!--you can wikilink to a subpage, but you can't wikilink to a subpage from within a ux template, apparently-->\n# {{senseid|en|rock through which a vein of ore or coal runs}} {{lb|en|mining}} The [[rock]] through which a [[vein]] of [[ore]] or [[coal]] runs.\n#: {{cot|en|gangue#Noun|overburden#Noun}}\n\n====Usage notes====\nThe geographical sense of \"country\" usually refers to a [[sovereign state]], that is, a nation with no administrative dependence on another one, which is the definition adopted in most world maps. In a broader sense, however, \"country\" may also refer to polities, or their territories, with some degree of autonomy and cultural identity but still under the sovereignty of another state. Examples of the latter include [[Scotland]], [[Tibet]], [[Abkhazia]], and [[Greenland]]. Such usage may be interpreted as supporting [[secessionism]] of these polities by others.\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col|en|anticountry|backcountry|countrification|countryball|countryfication|countryfolk|countryful|countryhood|countryhuman|countryish|countryless|countrylike|countrymade|countryman|countrymate|countryperson|countryship|countryward|countrywards|countrywear|countrywoman|cuntry|frontcountry|intercountry|intracountry|Lowcountry|microcountry|multicountry|noncountry|transcountry|live off the country\n|line of country|country mouse|country risk\n|accession country\n|across country\n|alt-country|summer country|winter country\n|alternative country\n|another country heard from\n|a prophet has no honor in his own country\n|a prophet is not without honor save in his own country\n|back country|country bread\n|Black Country\n|bro-country,bro country\n|coal country\n|Constable country\n|constituent country|safe third country\n|cottage country\n|countrify\n|country & western,country and western,country-and-western\n|country beam\n|country beer|country dweller\n|country blues,country-blues\n|country bookie\n|country box|go back to your country\n|country bumpkin\n|country captain\n|country club\n|country code\n|country cousin\n|country damage\n|country-damaged\n|country dance,country-dance\n|country dancing\n|country fig\n|country-fried\n|country-fried steak\n|country gentleman\n|country gravy\n|country ham\n|country house\n|country Joan\n|country lane\n|country merchant\n|country mile\n|country music\n|country of origin\n|country of provenance\n|country park\n|country pop\n|country punk\n|country rap\n|country road\n|country-rock\n|country rock\n|country sausage\n|country seat\n|country ship\n|country-side\n|country side\n|countryside\n|country stop\n|country store\n|country team\n|country-western\n|country-western music\n|countrywide\n|country wife\n|country wine\n|cross-country\n|cross country\n|cross-country ski\n|cross-country skier\n|cross-country skiing\n|cross country skiing\n|developed country\n|Elvis country\n|flyover country\n|foreign country\n|free country\n|fresh country egg\n|fresh country eggs\n|go country\n|God's country\n|God's own country\n|go to the country\n|hill country blues\n|home country\n|host country\n|in-country\n|in country\n|it's a free country\n|mini-independent country\n|model country\n|mother country\n|neotraditional country\n|new country project\n|Nordic country\n|north country\n|old-time country\n|outlaw country\n|outside country\n|pure country\n|socialism in one country\n|step-country\n|third country\n|tiger country\n|Trump country\n|up the country people\n|X-country\n}}\n\n====Descendants====\n{{top3}}\n* {{desc|jam|konchri}}\n* {{desc|kri|kɔntri}}\n* {{desc|pcm|kontri}}\n* {{desc|srn|kondre}}\n* {{desc|tpi|kantri}}\n* {{desc|ar|كَانْتْرِي|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|zh|港腳|tr=gǎngjiǎo|der=1}}\n* {{desc|fi|country|kantri|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|fr|country|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|hi|कंट्री|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|it|country|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|ja|カントリー|tr=kantorī|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|ko|컨트리|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|nb|køntri|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|nn|køntri|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|pl|country|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|pt|country|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|ro|country|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|ru|ка́нтри|bor=1}}\n** {{desc|kk|кантри|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|es|country|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|sv|country|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|da|country|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|uk|ка́нтрі|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|ur|کَنْٹْری|bor=1}}\n{{bottom}}\n\n====Translations====\n{{trans-top|region of land}}\n{{multitrans|data=\n* Afrikaans: {{tt+|af|land}}\n* Albanian: {{tt+|sq|vend|m}}, {{tt+|sq|krahinë|f}}\n* Altai:\n*: Southern Altai: {{t|alt|јака}}, {{t|alt|јер}}, {{t|alt|јурт}}\n* Amharic: {{tt|am|አገር}}, {{tt|am|ሀገር}}\n* Arabic: {{